metadata.name: The Color of Spring #52
metadata.description:
“Color of Spring” : Seasons of Siskiyou Series
By Ed Cavett
March 2022

Description of Seasons of Siskiyou Series
Surrounding my home, covering more than one million acres, is the Rogue River - Siskiyou National Forest which takes up three southern Oregon counties and one northern California county.  It’s a magical place that fills the imagination and lifts the spirit; a place that inspires with its uniqueness, its legends, and its larger-than-life vistas.

Each season in the Siskiyou mountains is a unique experience unto itself.  So, with an attention to the feelings this place evokes at any given time of the year, I designed four generative tokens to create an impression of the emotion–the calming quietness; the peaceful solitude; the overwhelming contrasts and variety of forms, shapes and textures; the magic and playful mystery; the welcomingness and foreboding.  These four works feature clever and inventive creative coding techniques in a rich, graphic style to craft a stunning impression of the Seasons of Siskiyou.


Token 1 of 4 - THE COLOR OF SPRING (1990 x 1080) p5js Generative Token.

The Color of Spring captures the playfulness and joy of the season of birth; the renewal and hopefulness of a bounty that follows warmth and light.  The weight of winter and the burdens of darkness melt away with the length of the day.  The monotones of a gray-chromatic winter bristle with bursts of bright colors in an ocean of budding green.  Magic brings forth the harbingers of fruit and the fleeting, nostalgic notes of newness and surprise.  In such a place, in such a time, we are transported back to when this was the world, and all there was in it.  With a child-mind, we are suspended in that instant while we relive all the moments like it.  And, before we have time to grow tired of it, it disappears into the brilliant light of summer.       

Output and Coding Features of “The Color of Spring”:

This generative token features a stand of aspen that borders a field of wildflowers in a sea of lush, green grass.  Animated pixies tend to the flowers as they wave their wands while fluttering about the field.  Fuzzy orbs of light dance around each pixie with some that glide capricious throughout the scene.

Press UP ARROW to toggle the scene on/off leaving only the pixies and glowing orbs.  Press RIGHT ARROW to toggle Pause and Play.  Press LEFT ARROW to toggle Add and Remove pixies.  The static scene has a blurry particle effect added in.  Press DOWN ARROW to save the current frame as a png image file.  The file will be downloaded to a local folder. 


Collectors can choose to pause the animation and freeze the scene on a static image.  If collectors so desire, they may remove the pixies from the scene and appreciate the simple beauty without distraction.  Capture an image as a downloadable image file by pressing the Down Arrow.

The aspens are generated using flow-field stochastic conditions for an organic structure, and with a random expression of knots as the object is formed.

The grass and flower pedals are generated using recursions that incorporate noise-stochastic conditions.

The pixies are generated with primitive geometries using a “marionette” style structure.  The animation is achieved through noise-stochastic conditions that rotate segments, such as the arms, legs and feet.

Each iteration varies the order and appearance of the graphic elements; the number of pixies and the number of flowers.   

Token Published April 16, 2022 on FXHASH set at 75 Editions.
Written and designed by Ed Cavett using the p5js library.
Token 1 of 4 from the series “The Seasons of Siskiyou.”

metadata.name: Klimtiche #71
metadata.description:
Inspired by the 'Tree of Life' by Gustav Klimt.
Every bird comes with a default weather setting but all weather is optional.
On the keyboard:
use 's' to make it snow
use 'w' to make wind blow
use 'r' to make it rain
use 'n' to stop the animation and then again to clear all animation. 
Variables are snow intensity, rain intensity, wind speed and palette.
Made in p5.js, every tree / meadow / sky is unique in design.
Two birds is rare.
Monochrome is rare.

metadata.name: Quasiflock #17
metadata.description:
Quasiflock is a 2022 rework of a 2006 realtime animated generative system, originally one of the projects from which later my toxiclibs library collection and some other big client projects & brand identities grew out of. The piece was part of a long, multi-year investigation into particle systems, agents and the aesthetic of fluid dynamics. Even though the approach used here is very primitive, my overall aim was to create a dynamic (and minimally interactive/responsive) system, which is above all mesmerizing to watch and somewhat feels alive. Since the original Java/Processing version isn't able to run anymore, I did some major updates and ported it to Zig & WebAssembly to give it a new life, more fluidity and a larger audience. Hope you enjoy!

10 parametric color themes (each with variations)
10 macro design/behavioral params (to control dozens more)
optionally mouse/touch responsive (rotate/pulsate)...

Made w/ Zig, WASM & thi.ng/umbrella

We live in a perpetual state of assertive belief, and the outside world never faults us, because we escape contradiction through a process of delusion. How reassuring it is to wander in the alleys of subjectivity and take a seat to look at these gardens we create.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #242
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Assemble #192
metadata.description:
Assemble is a 2D shape composition with a procedural background texture.

There are two types of shapes, squares and blobs, composed in a grid.

12 color palettes, procedurally generated using a GAN algorithm.

Available in [1:1] and [3:4] resolutions.

--------------------------------------------------

Keys [1-4]

1 - Variation (maintaining resolution)
2 - Variation (changing resolution)
3 - Change color (only in [3:4] resolution)
4 - Save canvas (Live View)

--------------------------------------------------

Made with p5.

-dePaula

metadata.name: De/Frag #288
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Mythologic #404
metadata.description:
"Mythologic" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Mythologic is a project derived from cloud series, Cloud Atlas and Requiem: Cloud on fxhash. In the series, lines and circles are used in an organics movement like Cloud Hands, which is a move of Tai Chi. Practitioners move their hands slowly and smoothly, make circles and rotate with extreme concentrating. In Chinese we said “floating clouds and flowing water” to describe calligraphers’ freely flowing style of writing. Chi is a very important for oriental artists, and for genart as well. In the series, lines and circles start from one position to another, and develop with organic rotations and movements, like practicing Tai Chi on the canvas. 

Mythologic was inspired from “Classic of Mountains and Seas”, also known as Shan Hai Jing, is a Chinese classic text and a compilation of mythic geography and beasts. 

“There is a beast that looks like a fox with nine tails.” 
“Huangbei: it is a beetle with meat like a tadpole, but with a head and a tail” 
“The beast has the body of a fish but the wings of a bird” 

There are many incredible creatures in the text which describe the oriental fantasy. The idea of Mythologic is to present an illustrated handbook with random generated paintings, each one is like a framed badge, to memorize the glorious age. It uses the "cloud hands" technique in every parts of this piece, the center, the circle and the frame. They are all the same algorithm but perform variety with different density and components. Gold, Silver, Copper, Jade and Ruby colors as noble symbol of treasure in Chinese culture. 

This project use p5js. 

Press 'S' to save pictures.

Thanks to the support of Yi-Wen Lin in this project.
